k&amp;merchantName=Crutchfield&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAATZ4NIvcZBcTai02AaeMjd5IbLD4uu_u_0Am3jC3ZZj7&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.crutchfield.com%2FS-XfCpHgEY1qk%2Fp_278LS11000%2FEpson-Home-Cinema-LS11000.html%3F">Epson Home Cinema LS11000 laser</a></h3><p><core-commerce id="a4b48b56f31d4674828bfffd24c3cfd5" data-type="product-list"></p><p> Fans of Epson&#39;s LCD projectors will be interested in <a data-i13n="cpos:52;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Crutchfield;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=3c3db68e-8b44-47ba-9267-2a00d1409126&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Crutchfield&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAATZ4NIvcZBcTai02AaeMjd5IbLD4uu_u_0Am3jC3ZZj7&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.crutchfield.com%2FS-XfCpHgEY1qk%2Fp_278LS11000%2FEpson-Home-Cinema-LS11000.html%3F">this model</a> , which received a big update in the form of a laser light source. That bumps the brightness to 2,500 ANSI lumens, and the three 1080p LCDs use a pixel shifter to quadruple the resolution to something close to true 4K. It offers very accurate colors with HDR10 and HLG capability, but is also great for gaming thanks to the 120 Hz refresh rate, 20-millisecond input lag and HDMI 2.1 support. You also get a 3-way motorized lens, scene adaptive correction and more for $4,000.</p><h3> <a data-i13n="cpos:53;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:B&amp;H Photo Video;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=95276f3c-7b79-4c1e-803f-981cd9f7a968&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=B%26H+Photo+Video&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAY1ujfNWhFMv078gPZ1bNZho17AcO6mi8HAw1o6WvZ0D&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bhphotovideo.com%2Fc%2Fproduct%2F1558726-REG%2Foptoma_technology_uhz65lv_4k_laser_projector.html"><strong>Optoma UHZ65LV</strong></a></h3><p><core-commerce id="45b4dc4ecaa04587bb88e4d16f6c497a" data-type="product-list"></p><p> Optoma&#39;s $6,000 <a data-i13n="cpos:54;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:B&amp;H Photo Video;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=95276f3c-7b79-4c1e-803f-981cd9f7a968&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=B%26H+Photo+Video&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAY1ujfNWhFMv078gPZ1bNZho17AcO6mi8HAw1o6WvZ0D&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.bhphotovideo.com%2Fc%2Fproduct%2F1558726-REG%2Foptoma_technology_uhz65lv_4k_laser_projector.html">UHZ65LV</a> also uses a long-lasting laser light source to deliver a 5,000 lumen image, much brighter than any lamp-powered projector. It also delivers true 4K resolution up to 60p, thanks to the TI 0.66-inch DLP chip. The extra brightness and contrast make it ideal for HDR10 or HLG content. It also comes with desirable features for a long-throw laser projector, like a 1.6x zoom and vertical lens shift.</p><h3> <a data-i13n="cpos:55;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAaL--baVgPrUTgXybOieqOdRAkLDlSqzD0RAeO2cxtVh&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FLG-HU810PW-CineBeam-Projector-DCI-P3%2Fdp%2FB08T4BW2CB"><strong>LG CineBeam HU810PW 4K</strong></a></h3><p><core-commerce id="d2aeb61cf2d54abdab9831f431dc54dd" data-type="product-list"></p><p> Speaking of long-throw laser projectors, LG&#39;s $3,000 <a data-i13n="cpos:56;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAaL--baVgPrUTgXybOieqOdRAkLDlSqzD0RAeO2cxtVh&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FLG-HU810PW-CineBeam-Projector-DCI-P3%2Fdp%2FB08T4BW2CB">CineBeam HU810PW</a> is another excellent pick at a much lower price point. There are some compromises, as the laser light pushes out a lower 2,700 lumens (that&#39;s still a lot), and it has a smaller 0.47-inch DLP chip that delivers slightly lower perceived resolution. However, it has dual blue and green lasers which help it deliver accurate HDR colors with an excellent 97 percent DCI-P3 coverage. It also offers a 1.6x zoom with lens shift and an HDMI 2.1 port that allows for 4K at 60p with up to 12-bit color depth. It comes with LG&#39;s webOS, so it supports Amazon Prime, Netflix, Hulu and other streaming services without the need for a dongle.</p><h3> <a data-i13n="cpos:57;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAcuSQgP3QNP4EuJ1xxw2UuCvn6yhBd93G4XWBsoG2yes&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FSony-Theater-Video-Projector-VPLVW295ES%2Fdp%2FB07GM3B89W"><strong>Sony VPL-VW295ES</strong></a></h3><p><core-commerce id="3c30af768bd4440ab52b98e4bb79c354" data-type="product-list"></p><p> If you&#39;re looking for a true, native 4K projector, Sony&#39;s $4,500 <a data-i13n="cpos:58;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAcuSQgP3QNP4EuJ1xxw2UuCvn6yhBd93G4XWBsoG2yes&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FSony-Theater-Video-Projector-VPLVW295ES%2Fdp%2FB07GM3B89W">VPL-VW295ES</a> is the least costly option out there. It&#39;s by far the sharpest 4K projector in this roundup, thanks to Sony&#39;s proprietary 4K SXRD native DCI 4K (4,096 x 2,160) panels. It also delivers extremely accurate colors, with 100 percent DCI-P3 coverage and HDR10/HLG support. You also get niceties like a 2.06 zoom lens with powered zoom, lens shift and focus. The main drawback is a relatively dim 1,500 lumen brightness, but it&#39;s a top pick if picture quality is paramount above all.</p><h2> Best budget portable projectors</h2><h3> <a data-i13n="cpos:59;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAanScaDEPOjaxf1DNB4q604LNFt88ArRMQ8FyaEuECcH&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FXGIMI-Portable-Projector-Android-Speakers%2Fdp%2FB08145121K">Xgimi MoGo Pro</a></h3><p><core-commerce id="ca3d6147dd1f4c42949940f5dde6a93b" data-type="product-list"></p><p> Xgimi is a relatively new brand, but has started to gain traction thanks to its lineup of portable projectors. The best mini projector is the <a data-i13n="cpos:60;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAanScaDEPOjaxf1DNB4q604LNFt88ArRMQ8FyaEuECcH&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FXGIMI-Portable-Projector-Android-Speakers%2Fdp%2FB08145121K">MoGo Pro</a> , which can be powered by a battery (with two hours of playtime) and is small enough to fit in a backpack. But this mini projector still delivers a detailed and reasonably accurate 1080p image, while offering automatic focus and vertical keystone adjustment. It even comes with Android TV, giving you all the streaming options you can need – all for $650.</p><h3> <a data-i13n="cpos:61;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9CZW5RLVdpcmVsZXNzLVByb2plY3Rvci1SZXNpc3RhbnQtQmx1ZXRvb3RoL2RwL0IwODU3NktNR04_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tM2otMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6IjJiNjQxMzE5LTQ3ZWMtNGQ2YS1iNDNjLTU1ODYxNWYxY2ZmZSJ9&amp;signature=AQAAATWlNylCai9S_dNE_MfN6-f9OuZdFKQxcs3DwxvU4tGP&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FBenQ-Wireless-Projector-Resistant-Bluetooth%2Fdp%2FB08576KMGN">BenQ GS2</a></h3><p><core-commerce id="e57a3ea948e9488ea496940453834172" data-type="product-list"></p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:62;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;custData=eyJzb3VyY2VOYW1lIjoiV2ViLURlc2t0b3AtVmVyaXpvbiIsInN0b3JlSWQiOiI2NmVhNTY3YS1jOTg3LTRjMmUtYTJmZi0wMjkwNGVmZGU2ZWEiLCJsYW5kaW5nVXJsIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYW1hem9uLmNvbS9CZW5RLVdpcmVsZXNzLVByb2plY3Rvci1SZXNpc3RhbnQtQmx1ZXRvb3RoL2RwL0IwODU3NktNR04_dGFnPWdkZ3QwYy1wLW8tM2otMjAiLCJjb250ZW50VXVpZCI6IjJiNjQxMzE5LTQ3ZWMtNGQ2YS1iNDNjLTU1ODYxNWYxY2ZmZSJ9&amp;signature=AQAAATWlNylCai9S_dNE_MfN6-f9OuZdFKQxcs3DwxvU4tGP&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FBenQ-Wireless-Projector-Resistant-Bluetooth%2Fdp%2FB08576KMGN">This $470 model</a> is designed specifically for outdoor entertainment, so it&#39;s battery-powered and splash and shock resistant – making it your best bet for backyard movie nights or for watching sports events, camping and more. It&#39;s also one of the brightest portable projectors out there and has a battery life of up to three hours. This outdoor projector only delivers 720p resolution, but it does come with a streaming app in the form of Aptoide TV.</p><h3> <a data-i13n="cpos:63;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAYUtshjljwzbIp1T7gXkWTieVIpga8j3h3BocxnAwrpc&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FAnker-Portable-Projector-Autofocus-Correction%2Fdp%2FB089GPQJ4R%3F">Anker Nebula Solar HD</a></h3><p><core-commerce id="3373896fba334925891abc612a1aec90" data-type="product-list"></p><p> <a data-i13n="cpos:64;pos:1;elm:affiliate_link;sellerN:Amazon;elmt:" href="https://shopping.yahoo.com/rdlw?merchantId=66ea567a-c987-4c2e-a2ff-02904efde6ea&amp;siteId=us-engadget&amp;pageId=1p-autolink&amp;featureId=text-link&amp;merchantName=Amazon&amp;&amp;signature=AQAAAYUtshjljwzbIp1T7gXkWTieVIpga8j3h3BocxnAwrpc&amp;gcReferrer=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FAnker-Portable-Projector-Autofocus-Correction%2Fdp%2FB089GPQJ4R%3F">This 1080p projector</a> has a pretty rich feature set considering the $600 price including a battery. This portable projector delivers 400 lumens for reasonably bright outdoor use, has a reasonably powerful 2x3W speaker system with Dolby Digital Plus, comes with Android TV and has a built-in stand for easy adjustment.</p><h2>常见问题解答</h2><h3>Are 4K projectors better?</h3><p> Yes, because higher resolution is more noticeable on larger screens, so 4K is particularly useful with projectors since they beam images up to 200 inches in size. That being said, brightness and contrast are more important.</p><h3> Is a projector better than a TV?</h3><p> Projectors can provide a more immersive experience thanks to the large screen, but they&#39;re not necessarily “better.” Since you usually have to dim the lights with a projector, TVs are superior for everyday use.</p><h3> Is 2000 lumens bright enough for a projector?</h3><p> Yes, 2000 lumens is easily bright enough, even with some ambient light in the room. However, the image will still be hard to see with the windows open on a bright day.</p><h3> Should I get a 4K or 1080p projector?</h3><p> That depends on your budget and needs. If your budget is below $1,000, look for a 1080p projector with the best brightness and contrast. Between $1,000-$2,000, you&#39;ll need to weigh whether brightness or 4K resolution is most important. Above that, choose the brightest 4K projector you can afford.</p><h3> What are the best projectors in daylight?</h3><p> The best projectors in daylight are ultra short throw (UST) models, as they have the brightest and sharpest image. However, they generally cost more than $2,000.</p> This article originally appeared on Engadget at https://www.engadget.com/best-projectors-123004354.html?src=rss]]>; </description><link/><![CDATA[https://www.engadget.com/best-projectors-123004354.html?src=rss]]><source_id> engadget_479</source_id><guid ispermalink="false"> 2b641319-47ec-4d6a-b43c-558615f1cffe</guid><dc:creator> Steve Dent</dc:creator><source/><![CDATA[Engadget]]><dc:publisher> Engadget</dc:publisher><dc:rightsholder> Engadget</dc:rightsholder><pubDate> Wed, 05 Jul 2023 14:45:34 +0000</pubDate><ingested> 1688568335</ingested><modified> 2023-07-05T14:45:50+00:00 </modified><category><![CDATA[Technology & Electronics]]></category><category><![CDATA[site|engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[provider_name|Engadget]]></category><category><![CDATA[region|US]]></category><category><![CDATA[language|en-US]]></category><category><![CDATA[author_name|Steve Dent]]></category><media:content height="1265" medium="image" url="https://s.yimg.com/os/creatr-uploaded-images/2021-04/e0b47780-92ed-11eb-bffb-1cf00cf593cb" width="2000"><media:keywords> headline </media:keywords><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[1]]></dc:identifier><media:credit><![CDATA[ ]]></media:credit><media:description><![CDATA[ ]]></media:description><media:title><![CDATA[ ]]></media:title></media:content><media:content height="1265" medium="image" url="https://media-mbst-pub-ue1.s3.amazonaws.com/creatr-uploaded-images/2021-04/e0b47780-92ed-11eb-bffb-1cf00cf593cb" width="2000"><media:media_html><![CDATA[ ]]></media:media_html><dc:identifier><![CDATA[